---
name: codebase-archaeologist
description: >
  Deep analysis skill for Java applications using JSF, Spring MVC, or Spring Boot.
  Trigger this whenever someone has a Java+JSF or Java+Spring repository and wants
  to understand it, document it, or generate business/product requirements from it.
  Common triggers: "analyze this Java project", "what does this Spring Boot app do?",
  "explain this JSF application", "generate a PRD from this codebase", "document this
  Java app", "onboard me to this project", "what is the architecture?", "reverse
  engineer requirements from code", "create product documentation", "I inherited this
  Java project", "map this Spring application", "audit this JSF app".
  Produces: Tech Stack Card, Architecture Map, Data Model, API/Screen Inventory,
  Business Rules extraction, and a full Product Requirements Document (PRD).
  ALWAYS use this skill for Java+JSF or Java+Spring analysis — never freeform.
---

# Codebase Archaeologist — Java / JSF / Spring Edition 🏛️

Analyzes Java applications (JSF, Spring MVC, Spring Boot) and produces structured
knowledge artifacts including a **Product Requirements Document (PRD)** reverse-engineered
from the codebase. Covers Java 6 through Java 25, all Spring and JSF generations.

---

## STEP 0 — TRIAGE (Always run first)

```bash
# 1. Project shape
find . -maxdepth 3 \
  -not -path '*/.git/*' -not -path '*/target/*' -not -path '*/build/*' \
  -not -path '*/node_modules/*' -not -path '*/__pycache__/*' \
  | sort

# 2. Build files — foundation of all analysis
find . \( -name "pom.xml" -o -name "build.gradle" -o -name "build.gradle.kts" \
  -o -name "settings.gradle" -o -name "settings.xml" \) \
  -not -path '*/target/*' | sort

# 3. Web descriptor and config
find . \( -name "web.xml" -o -name "faces-config.xml" -o -name "*.xhtml" \
  -o -name "application.properties" -o -name "application.yml" \
  -o -name "application-*.properties" -o -name "applicationContext*.xml" \
  -o -name "spring*.xml" -o -name "beans*.xml" \
  \) -not -path '*/target/*' | sort

# 4. Java source roots
find . -type d -name "java" -not -path '*/target/*' | head -5
find . -type d -name "src" -not -path '*/target/*' | head -5

# 5. JSF/Facelets views
find . \( -name "*.xhtml" -o -name "*.jsf" -o -name "*.faces" \) \
  -not -path '*/target/*' | sort

# 6. Test presence
find . -type d \( -name "test" -o -name "it" -o -name "integration-test" \) \
  -not -path '*/target/*' | head -5
```

Write a **First Impression** (3 sentences): tech generation, apparent domain, overall health.

---

## STEP 1 — STACK IDENTIFICATION

**Always read `references/jvm-stack.md` before proceeding.**

Then produce the Tech Stack Card:

```
╔══════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗
║              TECH STACK CARD                         ║
╠══════════════════════════════════════════════════════╣
║ Java Version   : [e.g. Java 8 / 11 / 17 / 21]       ║
║ UI Framework   : [JSF 1.x / 2.x / 3.x / 4.x]        ║
║                  [PrimeFaces / RichFaces / ICEfaces]  ║
║                  [Spring MVC + Thymeleaf / FreeMarker]║
║ Backend        : [Plain Spring 3/4/5 / Spring Boot   ║
║                   1.x / 2.x / 3.x]                   ║
║ Config Style   : [XML beans / Annotation / Boot auto] ║
║ Build Tool     : [Maven / Gradle]                     ║
║ Persistence    : [Spring Data JPA / Hibernate /       ║
║                   MyBatis / jOOQ / plain JDBC]        ║
║ Database       : [type + version if detectable]       ║
║ Security       : [Spring Security version / JAAS /    ║
║                   custom / none]                      ║
║ App Server     : [Tomcat / JBoss / WildFly /          ║
║                   WebLogic / embedded]                ║
║ Messaging      : [Kafka / RabbitMQ / JMS / none]      ║
║ Key Libraries  : [top 8 by importance]                ║
║ Test Coverage  : [JUnit 4/5 + Mockito / none]         ║
║ ⚠️ Flags       : [deprecated APIs, EOL versions, etc] ║
╚══════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝
```

