## STEP 2 — ARCHITECTURE MAP

### 2a. Module structure
```bash
# Maven multi-module
grep "<module>" pom.xml settings.xml 2>/dev/null | head -20

# Gradle multi-project
cat settings.gradle settings.gradle.kts 2>/dev/null | grep "include"

# Package structure (top-level domain packages)
find src/main/java -type d -maxdepth 5 -not -path '*/target/*' | sort | head -40
```

### 2b. Layering pattern — identify and name it

| Folder signals | Pattern name |
|---|---|
| `controller/` `service/` `repository/` `model/` | **Classic Spring Layered** |
| `bean/` `backing/` `managed/` + `.xhtml` views | **JSF ManagedBean / CDI** |
| `port/` `adapter/` `domain/` `application/` | **Hexagonal** |
| `command/` `query/` `handler/` | **CQRS** |
| Large classes, no clear structure | **Legacy / Big Ball of Mud** |

### 2c. Entry point chain

**For JSF apps:**
```
web.xml → FacesServlet (*.xhtml / *.jsf)
  └── faces-config.xml → navigation rules + managed beans
        └── @ManagedBean / @Named CDI bean
              └── @EJB / @Autowired service
                    └── @Repository / DAO
                          └── Database
```

**For Spring Boot apps:**
```
@SpringBootApplication: com.example.Application
  └── Autoconfiguration
        └── @RestController / @Controller
              └── @Service
                    └── @Repository (JpaRepository)
                          └── Database
```

**For Spring MVC (WAR) apps:**
```
web.xml → DispatcherServlet
  └── applicationContext.xml / @Configuration
        └── @Controller / @RequestMapping
              └── @Service
                    └── @Repository / DAO
                          └── Database
```

### 2d. Mermaid Architecture Diagram
Always generate this:

```mermaid
graph TB
    Browser["🌐 Browser"]
    
    subgraph "Presentation Layer"
        JSF["JSF/Facelets .xhtml\n(PrimeFaces components)"]
        MB["@ManagedBean / @Named\nBacking Beans"]
    end
    
    subgraph "Business Layer"
        SVC["@Service / @Stateless EJB\nBusiness Services"]
    end
    
    subgraph "Data Layer"
        REPO["@Repository / DAO\nSpring Data JPA"]
        DB[("Database\nPostgres / MySQL / Oracle")]
    end
    
    subgraph "Cross-Cutting"
        SEC["Spring Security\n/ JAAS"]
        TX["@Transactional"]
    end

    Browser --> JSF --> MB --> SVC --> REPO --> DB
    SEC -.-> MB
    TX -.-> SVC
```
Adapt this diagram to match what's actually in the codebase.

---

## STEP 3 — SCREEN & FEATURE INVENTORY (JSF)

For JSF applications, map every screen to its backing bean and function:

```bash
# All XHTML views
find . -name "*.xhtml" -not -path '*/target/*' | sort

# Managed beans / CDI beans
grep -rn "@ManagedBean\|@Named\|@ViewScoped\|@SessionScoped\|@RequestScoped\|@ApplicationScoped" \
  --include="*.java" . | grep -v test | grep -v target | head -40

# Navigation rules
cat src/main/webapp/WEB-INF/faces-config.xml 2>/dev/null | grep -A5 "navigation-rule"

# PrimeFaces / RichFaces component usage
grep -rn "p:\|rich:\|a4j:\|ice:" $(find . -name "*.xhtml" -not -path '*/target/*') \
  | sed 's/.*<\([a-z]*:[a-z]*\).*/\1/' | sort | uniq -c | sort -rn | head -20
```

Produce a **Screen Inventory Table**:

```
## Screen Inventory

| Screen (XHTML) | Backing Bean | Scope | Key Functions | Domain Area |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| login.xhtml | LoginBean | @RequestScoped | authenticate(), logout() | Auth |
| dashboard.xhtml | DashboardBean | @ViewScoped | loadSummary(), refresh() | Home |
| orders/list.xhtml | OrderListBean | @ViewScoped | search(), paginate(), export() | Orders |
| orders/create.xhtml | OrderCreateBean | @ViewScoped | save(), validate(), cancel() | Orders |
| ... | ... | ... | ... | ... |
```

---

## STEP 4 — API SURFACE (Spring MVC / REST)

```bash
# REST endpoints
grep -rn "@GetMapping\|@PostMapping\|@PutMapping\|@DeleteMapping\|@RequestMapping\|@PatchMapping" \
  --include="*.java" . | grep -v test | grep -v target | head -40

# Response types
grep -rn "ResponseEntity\|@ResponseBody\|produces.*json\|MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON" \
  --include="*.java" . | grep -v test | grep -v target | head -20

# OpenAPI / Swagger
find . \( -name "openapi*.yaml" -o -name "openapi*.json" \
  -o -name "swagger*.yaml" -o -name "swagger*.json" \) | grep -v target | head -5
```

Produce an **API Inventory Table**:

```
## API Endpoints

| Method | Path | Controller | Purpose | Auth Required |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| GET | /api/orders | OrderController | List all orders (paginated) | YES |
| POST | /api/orders | OrderController | Create new order | YES |
| GET | /api/orders/{id} | OrderController | Get order by ID | YES |
```

---

## STEP 5 — DATA MODEL

```bash
# JPA Entities
find . -name "*.java" -not -path '*/test*' -not -path '*/target/*' \
  | xargs grep -l "@Entity" 2>/dev/null | sort

# Read each entity file for fields and relationships
grep -rn "@Entity\|@Table\|@Column\|@Id\|@GeneratedValue\|@OneToMany\|@ManyToOne\|@ManyToMany\|@OneToOne\|@JoinColumn" \
  --include="*.java" . | grep -v test | grep -v target | head -60

# DB migrations (read latest 5 for schema truth)
find . \( -name "V*__*.sql" -o -path "*/db/migration/*.sql" -o -path "*/flyway/*.sql" \) \
  -not -path '*/target/*' | sort | tail -5 | xargs cat 2>/dev/null
```

Produce an **Entity Relationship Summary**:

```
## Core Domain Entities

### [EntityName]
- **Table**: `table_name`
- **Key Fields**: id (PK), field1, field2, ...
- **Relationships**: 
  - @OneToMany → [ChildEntity] (cascade ALL)
  - @ManyToOne → [ParentEntity]
- **Business Meaning**: [what this represents in the domain]

### ...
```

---

## STEP 6 — BUSINESS RULES EXTRACTION

This step reverse-engineers business logic from the code into human-readable rules.

```bash
# Validation logic
grep -rn "@NotNull\|@NotBlank\|@Size\|@Min\|@Max\|@Pattern\|@Valid\|@Validated" \
  --include="*.java" . | grep -v test | grep -v target | head -30

# Business exceptions (reveal rules)
find . -name "*Exception*.java" -o -name "*Error*.java" | grep -v target | head -20

# Status/state enums (reveal workflow)
find . -name "*.java" -not -path '*/test*' -not -path '*/target/*' \
  | xargs grep -l "^public enum" 2>/dev/null

# Conditional business logic
grep -rn "if.*status\|if.*role\|if.*type\|switch.*status" \
  --include="*.java" . | grep -v test | grep -v target | head -20

# Scheduled jobs
grep -rn "@Scheduled\|@EnableScheduling\|QuartzJobBean\|JobDetail" \
  --include="*.java" . | grep -v test | grep -v target | head -10
```

Produce a **Business Rules Register**:

```
## Business Rules Extracted from Code

### Validation Rules
- BR-001: [FieldName] must not be null (enforced by @NotNull on Entity.field)
- BR-002: [FieldName] must be between X and Y characters
- BR-003: [FieldName] must match pattern [regex] (e.g. email, phone)

### Workflow / State Rules  
- BR-010: Order can only transition: DRAFT → SUBMITTED → APPROVED → SHIPPED → DELIVERED
- BR-011: Only users with role ADMIN can approve orders
- BR-012: Orders > $10,000 require dual approval

### Calculated / Derived Rules
- BR-020: Total = sum(lineItems) + tax - discount
- BR-021: Tax rate applied based on customer region

### Scheduled Operations
- BR-030: [JobName] runs daily at [cron] — purpose: [inferred]

### Integration Rules
- BR-040: On order approval, notify [external system] via [method]
```

